		<tr>
			<td class="DetailName" style="width:20%;">Panel History:</td>
			<td colspan="5" class="bordered">
							&nbsp;</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailTitle" style="text-align:center;">
                            Summary on Grant Application Form</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailValue" style="padding:5px;">
                        <span id="lblAbstract">The research grant will fund Professor Russell, an expert in moving mesh methods, to visit Bath (with a short visit to Reading). There will be studies of three problems. Firstly we will construct two dimensional moving mesh methods based on scaling laws and will apply these to a series of PDE problems which exhibit finite blow-up. Secondly we will make a careful comparison of the variational (GCL) methods constructed by Russell with the parabolic Monge-Ampere methods of Budd in order to establish which is better (for a range of problems) on issues of cost, mesh quality and mesh tangling. Finally we will attempt to prove some fundamentatl theorems relating to the mesh distribution for one-dimensional methods applied to scale-invariant PDEs. This should aid an understanding of smoothing methods for such problems.</span>
                        </td>
		</tr>
